inscribe certain sexual acts and desires as criminal and sinful, including acts officially deemed to be “against nature”—sodomy, bestiality, and masturbation—along with others that approximated the unnatural—hermaphroditism, incest, sex with the devil, solicitation in the confessional, erotic religious visions, and the desecration of holy images. In doing so, this anthology makes important and necessary contributions to the historiography of gender and sexuality. Amid the growing politicized interest in broader LGBTQ movements in Latin America, the essays also show how these legal codes endured to make their way into post-independence Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLatin AmericansxSexual behaviorxHistory. 0aSex and lawzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSex crimeszLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSexzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSexzLatin AmericaxReligious aspectsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aBlack, Chad Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGermeten, Nicole von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoller, Jacqueline S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaffary, Nora E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavrin, Asunción, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolina, Fernanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenyak, Lee M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSigal, Pete, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilva, Martín Bowen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTortorici, Zeb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTortorici, Zeb, eeditor.4edt4htt